<paragraph pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
The nearly sessile leaves with truncate bases, the short inner petals bearing conspicuous basal hair tufts, and the thick-walled globose monocarps readily distinguish 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ulmaceae" genus="Xylopia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Xylopia letestui" order="Magnoliales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="letestui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Xylopia letestui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from its congeners. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName family="Annonaceae" genus="X." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. villosa" order="Magnoliales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">X. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both being large trees with narrow buttresses, leathery leaves that are appressed-pubescent beneath, and relatively large thick-walled monocarps. In addition to the truncate leaf bases and the hair tufts on the outer petals, 
<taxonomicName family="Annonaceae" genus="X." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. letestui" order="Magnoliales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" rank="species" species="letestui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">X. letestui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName family="Annonaceae" genus="X." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. villosa" order="Magnoliales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">X. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having abaxial leaf indument that is dull-colored, not golden-sericeous, and four or fewer flowers in the inflorescences. The sinuous young shoots with conduplicate new leaves sometimes seen in 
<taxonomicName family="Annonaceae" genus="X." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. letestui" order="Magnoliales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" rank="species" species="letestui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">X. letestui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have not been noted in specimens of 
<taxonomicName family="Annonaceae" genus="X." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. villosa" order="Magnoliales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">X. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The presence of 
<taxonomicName family="Annonaceae" genus="X." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. letestui" order="Magnoliales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" rank="species" species="letestui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">X. letestui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in West Africa was previously unreported (
<bibRefCitation author="Keay, RWJ" journalOrPublisher="Crown Agents for Oversea Governments and Administrations, London" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" refId="B92" refString="Keay, RWJ, 1954-1958. Flora of West Tropical Africa, second edition, Volume 1. Crown Agents for Oversea Governments and Administrations, London" title="Flora of West Tropical Africa, second edition, Volume 1." year="1954 - 1958">Keay 1954-1958</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Keay, RWJ" journalOrPublisher="Clarendon (Oxford University) Press, Oxford" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" refId="B93" refString="Keay, RWJ, 1989. Trees of Nigeria. Clarendon (Oxford University) Press, Oxford" title="Trees of Nigeria." year="1989">1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1079/9780851997346.0101" author="Holmgren, M" editor="Poorter, L" journalOrPublisher="CABI Publishing, Wallingford" pageId="186" pageNumber="187" pagination="101 - 390" refId="B74" refString="Holmgren, M, Poorter, L, Siepel, A, Bongers, F, Buitelaar, M, Chatelain, C, Gautier, L, Hawthorne, WD, Jongkind, CCH, Os-Breijer, H-J, Wieringa, JJ, van Zoest, AR, 2004. Chapter 9. Ecological profiles of rare and endemic species. In: Poorter, L, Bongers, F, Kouame, FN', Hawthorne, WD, Eds., Biodiversity of West African forests: an ecological atlas of woody plant species. CABI Publishing, Wallingford: 101 - 390, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1079/9780851997346.0101" title="Chapter 9. Ecological profiles of rare and endemic species." url="https://doi.org/10.1079/9780851997346.0101" volumeTitle="Biodiversity of West African forests: an ecological atlas of woody plant species." year="2004">Holmgren et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
), probably in part due to its similarity to 
<taxonomicName family="Annonaceae" genus="X." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. villosa" order="Magnoliales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">X. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which occurs over much of the same range. Associates listed on herbarium labels include 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Wild" authorityYear="1914" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Alstonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Alstonia boonei" order="Gentianales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="boonei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Alstonia boonei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pierre" authorityYear="1896" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Dichostemma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dichostemma glaucescens" order="Malpighiales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glaucescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Dichostemma glaucescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Podococcus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Podococcus barteri" order="Arecales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="barteri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Podococcus barteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(understory), 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Burseraceae" genus="Santiria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Santiria trimera" order="Sapindales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="trimera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Santiria trimera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benth" authorityYear="1849" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Tabernaemontana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tabernaemontana crassa" order="Gentianales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="crassa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Tabernaemontana crassa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Terminalia superba</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Uapaca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Uapaca guineensis" order="Malpighiales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="guineensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Uapaca guineensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
<bibRefCitation author="Le Thomas, A" editor="Aubreville, A" journalOrPublisher="Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris" pageId="188" pageNumber="189" pagination="1 - 371" refId="B109" refString="Le Thomas, A, 1969. 16: Annonacees. In: Aubreville, A, Ed., Flore du Gabon. Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris: 1 - 371" title="16: Annonacees." volumeTitle="Flore du Gabon." year="1969">Le Thomas (1969)</bibRefCitation>
distinguished two specimens from 
<collectingCountry name="Gabon">Gabon</collectingCountry>
with longer and denser indument as a separate variety, 
<taxonomicName family="Annonaceae" genus="X." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. letestui subsp. var. var. longepilosa" order="Magnoliales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" rank="variety" species="letestui" subSpecies="var." variety="longepilosa">X. letestui var. longepilosa</taxonomicName>
. We found density and length of hairs to vary over the range of the species, and that the densest hairs seem to accompany specimens bearing new flushes of growth, suggesting that the characteristic is variable and does not merit taxonomic recognition.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
The label of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Leeuwenberg 3073</emphasis>
describes the specimen as being from a large liana about 
<quantity metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" unit="m" value="25.0">25 m</quantity>
high, but this growth form has not been corroborated by any other specimen data, all of which describe the plant as an erect forest tree.
</paragraph>
